ULYSSES.

Ulysses, a celebrated Greek hero, took a prominent part in the long siege of Troy. After the fall oi the city, he set out with his followers on his homeward voyage to Ithac'a, an island of which he was king; but, being driven out oi his course by northerly winds, he was compelled to touch at the country oi the Lotus Eaters, who are supposed to have lived on the north coast oi Libya (Africa). Some of his comrades were so delighted with the lotus fruit that they wished to remain in the country, but Ulysses compelled them to embark again, and continued his voyage. He next came to the island of Sicily, and fell into the hands of the giant Polyphemus, one of the Cyclopes.
